      "final_response": "The \u201csuper thin / stubby section\u201d behavior can happen even when the model is fine \u2014 there are a couple spots in the backend that can *turn a half-step LLM reply into the final saved section*.\n\n- **Premature \u201cfinalization\u201d when the model forgets `Final Answer:`**: `ReportAgent._generate_section_react` will *accept whatever the model said* as the section content if (a) it\u2019s already made `>= 3` tool calls and (b) the reply has **no tool call** and **no `Final Answer:` marker**. If the model outputs a short \u201cThought/placeholder\u201d at that point, you get a thin stub. See `backend/app/services/report_agent.py:1470`+ (the \u201c\u60c5\u51b53\u201d branch) and the logging around `backend/app/services/report_agent.py:1511`.\n- **Content getting wiped by `<think>...</think>` stripping**: `LLMClient.chat` strips `<think>` blocks. If your provider/model sometimes wraps the *actual answer* inside `<think>`, this can collapse a full section down to near-empty. See `backend/app/utils/llm_client.py:66`.\n- **Cleaner can delete the only line(s) of a section**: when saving, `ReportManager.save_section` runs `_clean_section_content`, which removes a leading Markdown heading that matches the section title (first ~5 lines). If the model outputs basically just a title heading, the saved file becomes only `## {section.title}` plus little/nothing. See `backend/app/services/report_agent.py:2138` and the \u201cskip duplicate title\u201d logic at `backend/app/services/report_agent.py:2188`.\n\nI also put in a targeted mitigation so this stops happening as often:\n- `backend/app/services/report_agent.py:1287`+ now treats short/Thought-like replies (without `Final Answer:`) as suspicious and asks the model to output a proper `Final Answer:` instead of immediately accepting the stub.\n- `backend/app/utils/llm_client.py:66`+ now falls back to *unwrapping* `<think>` tags (instead of deleting everything) if stripping would otherwise return empty.\n- `backend/app/__init__.py:16` moves Flask imports inside `create_app` so importing `app.utils...` doesn\u2019t drag in Flask during tests.\n- Added tests for the `<think>` handling: `backend/tests/test_llm_client.py:1` (run with `cd backend && pytest -q tests/test_llm_client.py`)."
    }
